s © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Ithell</i> ‘son of <i>Ithel</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘bountiful lord’. This name was adopted in Wales and elsewhere as a name for a chapel, as it is a homograph of a Biblical placename meaning ‘house of God’ in Hebrew (Genesis 12, 13, 28, and elsewhere in the Bible).","German: habitational name from Bethel in Westphalia."],"variants":[{"name":"Bithell","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Bethel  ."]},{"name":"Ethel","meanings":["(2007: 236; 2010: NA)","Welsh: from the personal name <i>Ithell</i>, Middle Welsh <i>Ithael</i>. See   Bethel  ."]},{"name":"Bethea","meanings":["Possibly an altered form of Welsh   Bethel  .","History: The name was brought to VA by John Bethea (known as ‘English John’) (1684– after 1750), who settled in Nansemond, VA."]},{"name":"Bethell","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Bethel  ."]}]},{"name":"Marie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Maria .  When first introduced to England in the Middle Ages, it was Anglicized in pronunciation and respelled   Mary .  This French form was reintroduced into the English-speaking world as a separate name in the 19th century, and is still pronounced more or less in the French manner, although sometimes with the stress on the first syllable. It is now often used in combination with other names such as <i>Ellie</i>, <i>Chloe</i>, and <i>Lisa</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Marie de Réthel was born in 1245, in France, her father, Comte Manassès V de Réthel, was 41 and her mother, Isabelle de Dampierre-en-Astenois, was 36. She married Gauthier I d'Enghien about 1260, in Belgium. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in March 1316, in her hometown, at the age of 71."},"et":{"Cir 1245–March 1316":"1245–märts 1316","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1236–1275":"1236–1275","1238–1257":"1238–1257","1244–1285":"1244–1285","12